  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law in the United States, money laundering can result in serious criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Potential Imprisonment\n- Up to 20 years in federal prison per offense\n- Potential enhanced sentences for more complex cases\n- Consecutive sentences possible for multiple counts\n\n2. Financial Penalties\n- Substantial fines up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved\n- Potential forfeitures of assets connected to the laundering activity\n\n3. Additional Consequences\n- Criminal record\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Asset seizure\n- Potential deportation for non-citizens\n\n4. Specific Statutes\n- Prosecuted under 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 and \u00a7 1957\n- Charges can include money laundering, conspiracy, and related financial crimes\n\n5. Civil Penalties\n- potential civil penalties from the government\n- Additional financial sanctions\n\nThe exact penalties depend on specific circumstances, transaction amounts, prior criminal history, and case details. Federal prosecutors have significant discretion in pursuing charges.\n\nThese are general legal guidelines. For specific legal advice about a particular situation, consulting a qualified criminal defense attorney is recommended.",
